subsection.p:
A square matrix A is invertible if there is a matrix A^{-1} such that

  \boxed{
  A^{-1}A=AA^{-1}=I.
  }

If

  \mathbf y=A\mathbf x,

then

  \boxed{
  \mathbf x=A^{-1}\mathbf y.
  }

If

  A=
  \begin{pmatrix}
  a&b\\
  c&d
  \end{pmatrix},

then

  \boxed{
  A^{-1}
  =
  \frac{1}{ad-bc}
  \begin{pmatrix}
  d&-b\\
  -c&a
  \end{pmatrix}
  }

provided

  \boxed{
  ad-bc\ne0.
  }

To find A^{-1}, row reduce

  \boxed{
  [A\mid I].
  }

If A is invertible, then

  \boxed{
  A\mathbf x=\mathbf b
  \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
  \mathbf x=A^{-1}\mathbf b.
  }

If A and B are invertible, then

  \boxed{
  (AB)^{-1}=B^{-1}A^{-1}.
  }


  \boxed{
  (A^{-1})^{-1}=A.
  }


  \boxed{
  (A^T)^{-1}=(A^{-1})^T.
  }


  \boxed{
  (cA)^{-1}=\frac1c A^{-1}
  \qquad (c\ne0).
  }
